{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17647379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17647379"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:44:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:44:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18246"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18246"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10960"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81728"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10960"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18246"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67028"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7418"},{"type":"tags","id":"7422"},{"type":"tags","id":"7424"},{"type":"tags","id":"11401"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25469"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25474"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81728"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the attachment points of the iliofemoral ligament?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior superior iliac spine to the greater trochanter","Acetabular rim to the femoral neck","Ischial tuberosity to the lesser trochanter","Pubic symphysis to the femoral head","Anterior inferior iliac spine to the intertrochanteric line"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe iliofemoral ligament is a key structure in the hip joint, working to provide stability and preventing excessive movement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe correct attachment points for the iliofemoral ligament are from the \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior inferior iliac spine to the intertrochanteric line\u003C/strong\u003E of the femur. This ligament is crucial for stabilising the hip joint and preventing hyperextension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior superior iliac spine to the greater trochanter\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not the attachment for the iliofemoral ligament\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIschial tuberosity to the lesser trochanter\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the attachment of other structures, not the iliofemoral ligament\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPubic symphysis to the femoral head\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not a ligamentous attachment\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcetabular rim to the femoral neck\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the attachment of the capsular ligaments, not specifically the iliofemoral ligament\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The iliofemoral ligament is one of the strongest ligaments in the body and plays a crucial role in stabilising the hip joint.","The iliofemoral ligament attaches from the anterior inferior iliac spine to the intertrochanteric line of the femur.","This ligament helps prevent hyperextension of the hip joint during standing."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67028"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18246"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67028","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67028"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T20:39:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-26T20:40:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10960"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81728"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"headi